commit 79689c3bd2c779e1b3db654cc734489482b5bd07
Author: Marco Elver <elver@google.com>

kho: use checked arithmetic in deserialize_bitmap()

This commit updates deserialize_bitmap to use checked arithmetic for
calculating the memory reservation size and physical address. It aims to
prevent integer overflows and out-of-bounds updates caused by a corrupted
KHO image.

> Fix this by changing 'sz' to 'unsigned long' and using checked add and
> shift to safely calculate the shift amount, size, and physical address,
> skipping malformed chunks. This allows preserving memory with an order
> larger than MAX_PAGE_ORDER.

The commit message states that this change allows preserving memory with an
order larger than MAX_PAGE_ORDER. However, does the restore function fully
support this? The restore path contains a check that fails when the order
is greater than MAX_PAGE_ORDER, which would cause memory preserved with
these larger orders to leak.

> diff --git a/kernel/liveupdate/kexec_handover.c b/kernel/liveupdate/kexec_handover.c
> index cc68a3692905..0d8417dcd3ff 100644
> --- a/kernel/liveupdate/kexec_handover.c
> +++ b/kernel/liveupdate/kexec_handover.c

[ ... ]

> @@ -461,15 +462,29 @@ static void __init deserialize_bitmap(unsigned int order,
>  				      struct khoser_mem_bitmap_ptr *elm)
>  {
>  	struct kho_mem_phys_bits *bitmap = KHOSER_LOAD_PTR(elm->bitmap);

If a corrupt FDT image supplies 0 for the bitmap address, KHOSER_LOAD_PTR
returns a NULL pointer. Since the bitmap pointer is passed unconditionally
to for_each_set_bit below, can this result in a NULL pointer dereference
during early boot?

> +	unsigned int shift;
>  	unsigned long bit;
> +	unsigned long sz;

Is unsigned long sufficient for the size on 32-bit PAE architectures? A
contiguous physical memory block larger than 4GB would overflow a 32-bit
unsigned long, falsely rejecting valid physical chunks. memblock_reserve
uses phys_addr_t, so could sz be a phys_addr_t to avoid this truncation?

> +
> +	if (check_add_overflow(order, PAGE_SHIFT, &shift) ||
> +	    check_shl_overflow(1UL, shift, &sz)) {

On 64-bit systems, 1UL allows a shift up to 63. If a corrupt image supplies
an order of 51, this check passes without overflow, resulting in an 8
Exabyte size being passed to memblock_reserve below. Could the order be
bounded by a reasonable physical limit to prevent system hangs or out of
memory scenarios?

> +		pr_warn("invalid order %u for preserved bitmap\n", order);
> +		return;
> +	}
>  
>  	for_each_set_bit(bit, bitmap->preserve, PRESERVE_BITS) {
> -		int sz = 1 << (order + PAGE_SHIFT);
> -		phys_addr_t phys =
> -			elm->phys_start + (bit << (order + PAGE_SHIFT));
> -		struct page *page = phys_to_page(phys);
> +		phys_addr_t offset, phys;
>  		struct page *page;
>  		union kho_page_info info;
>  
> +		if (check_shl_overflow((phys_addr_t)bit, shift, &offset) ||
> +		    check_add_overflow(elm->phys_start, offset, &phys)) {
> +			pr_warn("invalid phys layout for preserved bitmap\n");
> +			return;
> +		}
> +
> +		page = phys_to_page(phys);

While the arithmetic overflow is prevented, does anything verify that the
resulting phys address or the original elm->phys_start points to valid
system RAM?

If an attacker provides an arbitrarily large but non-overflowing physical
address, phys_to_page can return an invalid pointer within the vmemmap
array. This would lead to a fatal page fault when page->private is updated.

Should these addresses be validated with pfn_valid or memblock_is_memory
before use?

> +
>  		memblock_reserve(phys, sz);
>  		memblock_reserved_mark_noinit(phys, sz);

